SIMPLE: spasmodic
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spasmodic
<hw>Spas"mod"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/; <?/ a
convulsion + <?/ likeness: cf. F. <ets>spasmotique</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to spasm; consisting
in spasm; occuring in, or characterized by, spasms; <as>as, a
<ex>spasmodic</ex> asthma</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Soon relaxed or exhausted; convulsive; intermittent;
<as>as, <ex>spasmodic</ex> zeal or industry</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Spasmodic croup</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>an
affection of childhood characterized by a stoppage of brathing developed
suddenly and without fever, and produced by spasmodic contraction of the
vocal cords. It is sometimes fatal. Called also <altname>laryngismus
stridulus</altname>, and <altname>childcrowing</altname>.</cd> --
<col><b>Spasmodic stricture</b></col>, <cd>a stricture caused by
muscular spasm without structural change. See <cref>Organic
stricture</cref>, under <er>Organic</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spasmodic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spasmodic
<hw>Spas*mod"ic</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A medicine
for spasm.</def><-- = antispasmodic -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spasmodical</ent>⟦br⟧
